### Abstract

This framework takes the cold fusion hypothesis as its starting point. The essence of cold fusion is regarded as the complementary weaving of topological defects on the surfaces of nuclides (Pathway I): when the defects of two nuclides are exactly complementary, they spontaneously interlock and release stress energy. The sole threshold is geometric matching, independent of energy barriers. The single-reaction probability of this mechanism is extremely low and depends on the nuclide type and environmental conditions. Using observed astrophysical heat fluxes as constraints, the macroscopic effective probability of Pathway I is inferred to be approximately \(10^{-29}\) under solar core conditions and approximately \(10^{-32}\) under Jupiter whole-body weighted conditions. When the particle number reaches an astrophysical scale (\(>10^{57}\)), this extremely low probability is statistically locked into an observable macroscopic event rate. Inside a neutron star, owing to ultra-high density, a strong anisotropic stress field in the solid state, and continuous compression, the effective reaction rate far exceeds that of the solar core. The energy released by Pathway I causes a localized central region of the star to cross the triggering threshold for Pathway II (forced chain reconnection). Pathway II is triggered in the high-energy core region with a small proportion of participating nuclides, releasing a shock wave and producing a pulse. The shock wave propagation speed in the solid medium is estimated to be on the order of \(0.3c\) to \(c\), traversing the entire star in approximately 0.03–0.1 ms. After the pulse is released, the star returns to Pathway I, re-accumulates energy, and forms a cycle. This single mechanism provides a unified explanation for all observed characteristics—including period, width, profile, glitches, magnetars, and the death line—without requiring additional assumptions such as magnetic inclination angle, superfluid vortices, or extreme magnetic fields.

**Keywords:** pulsars; dense topological star; defect complementary weaving; forced chain reconnection; total compressive binding energy; shock wave; cold fusion

