### Introduction

Cold fusion—the spontaneous combination of nuclides at low temperatures releasing energy—has been rejected by the standard model on the grounds that the reaction probability is too low at laboratory scales and the signal lies far below the detection threshold.

However, the astrophysical scale is entirely different. A compact star contains approximately \(10^{57}\) nuclides. Even if the interlocking probability per collision is extremely low, the absolute number can still reach a macroscopically significant event count. The law of large numbers locks the microscopic probability into a determined macroscopic statistical event rate. In the solar core, the macroscopic heat release power of Pathway I matches the observed luminosity; in Jupiter's interior, the macroscopic heat flow of Pathway I accounts for the observed excess radiation. Pathway I has never been falsified; it simply becomes observable only on astrophysical scales.

From this starting point, this paper reinterprets the entire observational phenomenology of pulsars.

A pulsar is a solid compact remnant. In its interior, gravity continuously compresses, and nuclides persistently release minute amounts of heat through defect complementary weaving (Pathway I), accumulating stress in the topological network. Because the total particle number is enormous, even if only a tiny fraction of nuclides participate in reactions, the absolute number is still sufficient to produce macroscopically observable effects, causing a localized central region of the star to cross the triggering threshold for Pathway II.

When the stress accumulated in the central local region reaches the total compressive binding energy (\(E_{\text{comp}}\)), Pathway II is triggered—connection edges are sheared off in batches, and chain reconnection releases a shock wave on a millisecond timescale. The shock wave propagates through the solid star toward the entire surface, producing a "spallation-like" fragmentation ejection. An observer can receive signals only from an extremely narrow line-of-sight direction.

After a pulse, the star returns to the Pathway I state, re-accumulates stress, and awaits the next triggering. The cycle repeats.

