### 1 Observational Facts of Pulsars

Since the discovery of the first pulsar by Hewish et al. in 1967, the accumulated observational parameters are as follows:

| Parameter | Typical Value/Range |
|-----------|---------------------|
| Pulse period \(P\) | 1.4 ms – 8.5 s |
| Period derivative \(\dot{P}\) | \(10^{-21}\) – \(10^{-11}\) s/s |
| Pulse width \(W\) | 1 – 50 ms (3%–4% of the period) |
| Radio luminosity | \(10^{24}\) – \(10^{31}\) erg/s |
| Characteristic age \(\tau = P/(2\dot{P})\) | \(10^{3}\) – \(10^{7}\) yr |
| Surface magnetic field (inferred) | \(10^{8}\) – \(10^{13}\) G |

Pulse profiles are diverse (single peak, double peak, multiple peaks). Some pulsars exhibit nulling (pulses suddenly disappear and then recover), subpulse drifting, and sudden period changes (glitches, \(\Delta P/P \sim 10^{-9}\)–\(10^{-6}\)). Magnetars (soft gamma repeaters, anomalous X-ray pulsars) have luminosities far exceeding their spin-down luminosity and radiate up to X-ray/γ-ray bands.

