### 7 Conclusion

The standard model's explanation of pulsars rests on multiple auxiliary assumptions—magnetic inclination, superfluid vortices, extreme magnetic fields, and an uncertain equation of state—and its prediction of a death line has been falsified by observations.

The topological defect weaving framework, with a single mechanism—the stress accumulation–trigger–release cycle—provides a unified explanation for all pulsar observational phenomena:

- Pulsars are solid compact remnants;
- A tiny proportion of nuclides independently release energy through Pathway I on a statistical basis, driving a localized central region across the \(E_{\text{comp}}\) threshold;
- Pathway II is triggered with a small proportion of participating nuclides in the central high-energy region, releasing a shock wave (speed about 0.3c to \(c\));
- The pulse is a natural result of the shock wave plus the line-of-sight window, not dependent on rotation or magnetic axis tilt;
- The period is the stress accumulation time; stability originates from the statistically locked event rate of the law of large numbers—the number of Pathway I events per period for the whole star far exceeds \(10^{30}\), and the period fluctuation is naturally at the femtosecond level or below;
- The period increase stems from the evolution of macroscopic parameters due to mass loss;
- The energy cycle is self-sustaining: the total energy released by Pathway I in one cycle far exceeds the energy of a single Pathway II shock wave (by 5–18 orders of magnitude);
- Glitches and magnetars are different scales of the same mechanism;
- The death line is a gradual process.

A pulsar is not a rotating lighthouse, but a solid compact star that, under gravitational confinement, repeatedly crosses a critical threshold and releases a shock wave—a stress accumulation–trigger–release cycle.

